## Example 4 — Find Inverses of Exponential Functions

The air pressure outside of an aircraft can be determined by:

`P = B(10^(-9h/100))`

where `B` is the air pressure at sea level and `h` is the altitude in miles. If the air pressure at sea level is `14.7` pounds per square inch, write an equation to find the height of an aircraft when the air pressure is known.

Substitute `14.7` for `B`:

`P = 14.7(10^(-9h/100))`

Divide by `14.7`:

`P/14.7 = 10^(-9h/100)`

Write in logarithmic form:

`log10(P/14.7) = -9h/100`

Solve for `h`:

`h = (-100/9) log10(P/14.7)`

